UPDATE — impl-review it1 fix: IMPL-FUND-1 (onQuote zero-cap guard), 2026-07-08
============================================================

Fresh Opus adversary impl-review iteration 1 = FAIL, 1 blocking finding
(IMPL-FUND-1; the other 3 dimensions — money-path (elsewhere), backward-compat,
real-binary — all PASS): `deposit`'s `payOnce()` call had NO `onQuote` callback.
`manual-x402.ts`'s `probeAndSign()` signs WHATEVER the server's real 402 response
quotes UNLESS the caller's `onQuote` aborts it first — an "expected $0" SERVER
-SIDE comment is not itself a CLIENT-SIDE enforcement. Every other paid command
(video/music/speech/realface) already reverifies a real quote against a budget cap
via `onQuote` before signing (REQ-220) — `deposit` was the one call site missing
this pattern.

Fix: `src/commands/wallet.ts`'s `payOnce()` call for the onramp mint now passes an
`onQuote` callback that THROWS when the quoted amount is a positive, non-null
number, BEFORE `createPaymentPayload` is ever invoked (per `payOnce()`'s own
documented "throwing here aborts the whole call — no signature is ever produced"
contract) — a genuine client-side zero-cap guard. The throw is caught by the
SAME graceful-degradation path REQ-FUND-006 already established (`ok()`, never
`fail()`), with the abort reason folded into `note`.

Spec updated: REQ-FUND-003 corrected from "the endpoint is $0 by design" (a
server-trust framing) to "SHALL pass an onQuote callback that aborts on any
non-zero quote" (a client-enforced framing); REQ-FUND-017 similarly reworded.
New PROP-FUND-014 added to verification-architecture.md, with 2 new tests in
test/integration/wallet.test.ts: (1) a mock `payOnce()` that invokes the REAL
`onQuote` callback with a non-zero amount BEFORE resolving — asserts the
would-be-minted URL NEVER surfaces and the command still exits 0 gracefully;
(2) the SAME mechanism with a genuine $0/null quote — asserts the mint proceeds
normally (proving the guard is a zero-only gate, not an unconditional abort).

